===Etymology===
Old English ''[[mil#Old English|mīl]]'', from a Germanic borrowing of Latin {{term|milia|mīlia|lang=la}}, {{term|millia|mīllia|lang=la}}, plural of {{term|mile|mīle|lang=la}}, {{term|mille|mīlle|mile|lang=la}} (literally ‘thousand’ but used as a short form of ''[[mille]] [[passus]]'' ‘a thousand paces’).  Cognate with Dutch {{term|mijl|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Meile|lang=de}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|/maɪ̯l/}}
* {{audio|en-us-mile.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|aɪl}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A unit of measure (length or distance) equal to 5,280 [[feet]] (8 [[furlong]]s) in the U.S.Customary/[[imperial|Imperial]] system of measurements. One mile is equal to 1.609344 km. <ref> http://www.onlineconversion.com/length_common.htm</ref>
# A Roman unit of measure equal to 1000 (double) steps (mille passus or mille passuum) or 5000 Roman feet (approx. 1480m).
# A track race of one mile in length; sometimes used to refer to the 1500m race.
#: ''The runners competed in the '''mile'''.''
# {{slang}} A great distance.
#: ''The shot missed by a '''mile'''.''
# {{informal}} One mile [[per]] [[hour]], as a [[measure]] of [[speed]].
#: ''five '''miles''' over the speed limit''

